<paper id="1713142183"><title>Symbolic verification of communication protocols with infinite state spaces using QDDs</title><year>1996</year><authors><author org="Université de Liège**" id="245983289">Bernard Boigelot</author><author org="Lucent Technologies Bell Laboratories#TAB#" id="2634395717">Patrice Godefroid</author></authors><n_citation>127</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1550288578</reference><reference>1550523972</reference><reference>1593428110</reference><reference>1957511817</reference><reference>1978358700</reference><reference>1981808971</reference><reference>1985925577</reference><reference>1994564174</reference><reference>2001426769</reference><reference>2017140475</reference><reference>2025970201</reference><reference>2030224590</reference><reference>2090398333</reference><reference>2106001218</reference><reference>2110697379</reference><reference>2117189826</reference><reference>2123160677</reference><reference>2331953749</reference><reference>2688386367</reference></references><venue id="1162450063" type="C">Computer Aided Verification</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-61474-5_53</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.44083">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.48332">Finite set</keyword><keyword weight="0.40068">Subclass</keyword><keyword weight="0.45737">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Symbolic verification</keyword><keyword weight="0.46728">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.55224">Decidability</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Fifo queue</keyword><keyword weight="0.56691">Deadlock prevention algorithms</keyword><keyword weight="0.44733">Distributed computing</keyword><keyword weight="0.51603">Communications protocol</keyword><keyword weight="0.51634">Undecidable problem</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We study the verification of properties of communication protocols modeled by a finite set of finite-state machines that communicate by exchanging messages via unbounded FIFO queues. It is well-known that most interesting verification problems, such as deadlock detection, are undecidable for this class of systems. However, in practice, these verification problems may very well turn out to be decidable for a subclass containing most “real” protocols.</abstract></paper>